Environment-climate: for a European New Deal
BRUXELLES – In Brussels as well as in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it is about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The European Union's commitment on these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
Later in 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a driving role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (baseline: 1990 levels).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not sufficient to meet the challenges facing today's world.
Rising temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of the Arctic sea ice by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is pervasive in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
Yet we have reasons to remain optimistic.
Look at these people, growing in number every day, ready to act to question their ways of life. Like these students and entire families marching in the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursday!
Companies are also committing themselves, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the politicians and policymakers, at both the national and European levels, who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let's make a green Europe our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three key areas.
Firstly, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit planetary warming to 1.5°C, we have no choice: the EU's net carbon dioxide emissions must be reduced to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can massively invest in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings and renewable energy, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we must also impose strict CO2 emission limits on new passenger cars, public transport, as well as maritime and air commercial transport.
And, by working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent for electric vehicles by 2030.
Secondly, Europe must play a leading role in the responsible use of resources and become a true waste-saving circular economy.
Every year, 8 billion tonnes of materials are converted into energy or products within the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tonnes come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require focusing on four areas: food waste and the bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us get to work today, for example by launching a European initiative to combat the planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronic devices, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wild species populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations biodiversity conference, which will be held in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must set the example.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a real debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to support this green transition.
But these colossal tasks that await us, we will not be able to accomplish them if it is always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear their costs.
All measures considered must therefore first and foremost be designed to minimize social costs.
And in parallel, we must start working today with our partners for international cooperation, fighting against unfair competition.
Because it serves no purpose to have strict European rules regarding pesticides or forest management if our imported food and wood are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three initiatives could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a severe ecological debt situation, and it would be more than justified for the stability and growth pact that applies to the public finances of member states to have an equivalent for the goals of a green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action in all areas: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not fear using its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of legislation on eco-design and extended producer responsibility for products on the market could significantly boost environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in investments each year to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
This is an achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral climate-focused funding provider.
And the new EU budget and investment plan, making the best use of private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union's capacity for action.
The financial sector will have to play a fundamental role: through the disclosure of climate-related financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as the Norwegian sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a long-term vision and avoid what Bank of England Governor Mark Carney called the "tragedy of the horizon."
Finally, although some member states may see it as a risky project, we must hold a debate on taxation, as well as on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, on the integration of sustainability into public spending.
Behind these projects, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must set ambitious goals and "missions" for the short and long term that have real societal resonance.
With the member states and the European Parliament, we will have to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as we will with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
All of this cannot be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to escape the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal". But it is not too late.
Let us not miss this new opportunity!
